<section class="hero">
  <h1>Lump Sum or <em>Ladder In?</em></h1>
  <div class="hero-subtitle">Two ways to put money into Bitcoin &mdash; and which one served you better depended on where price sat in the channel.</div>
  <p class="subtitle">A look back at how lump-summing and laddering in compared across Bitcoin&rsquo;s history &mdash; and how the comparison shifts with where price sits in its Power Law channel. A demonstration, not advice for your situation.</p>
</section>

<main class="content-area">

  {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

  <div class="section-intro lsl-prose">
    <p>Accumulating Bitcoin can involve both a lump sum and DCA. This page looks at how the two compared historically, and how that comparison shifts with where price sits in its Power Law channel.</p>
    <p class="lsl-footnote"><strong>DCA</strong> &mdash; dollar-cost averaging: deploying a fixed amount on a regular cadence (e.g. every paycheck) as a savings discipline, rather than all at once.</p>
    <p>Looking back at Bitcoin&rsquo;s price history, the rule of thumb is that a lump-sum buy has, on average, outperformed spreading the same money out over time. Markets trend up, and time in the market beats waiting on the sidelines.</p>
    <p>But that average hides something useful. The lump-sum-versus-ladder choice isn&rsquo;t really about <em>timing</em>, and not really about <em>market sentiment</em> &mdash; it tracks valuation relative to the Power Law trend. Low in the channel, you&rsquo;re effectively buying at a discount to trend: if you hold the Power Law thesis, price tends to revert upward over time, so deploying decisively captured more Bitcoin. Higher in the channel, the gap between lump-sum and laddering narrowed, and laddering more often came out ahead. <span class="lsl-aside">(Why that is &mdash; and why it&rsquo;s a weaker reed to lean on than it looks &mdash; is the subject of the next page.)</span></p>
    <p>And underneath all of it: historically, over a long enough horizon, <em>every</em> entry &mdash; even the literal worst tops in Bitcoin&rsquo;s history &mdash; has recovered to a large multiple. What this page explores is tactics, but commitment is the foundation.</p>
  </div>

